Gathering Data¶

The dataset was found on kaggle, and it comes from the Ames Housing dataset.

The Ames Housing dataset was compiled by Dean De Cock for use in data science education. It's an incredible alternative for data scientists looking for a modernized and expanded version of the often cited Boston Housing dataset.

In [314]:
data = pd.read_csv('/kaggle/input/house-prices-advanced-regression-techniques/train.csv')

According to the data description, the null values for the categorical data correspond to not having that feature in the house, so filling that with a new categorical value, DNE, should be a good treatment.

The missing quantitative data is bit more interesting. We could fill those null values with 0, or the mean of the other values. GarageYrBlt values should probably be set to the mean or even the YearBuilt, but we'll start with 0. With the amount of 0 values from MasVnrArea, it's questionable how much this feature contributes and if the data is even valid, since all but 4 houses have a Masonry veneer type but more than half have no recorded area. This feature may be a good candidate for removal.

Quantitative Data¶

In [325]:
rows = math.ceil(len(quantitative)/3)

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5*rows))

for n in range(0, len(quantitative)):
    plt.subplot(rows, 3, n+1)
    sns.regplot(x=data[quantitative[n]], y=data.SalePrice, line_kws={'color':'cyan'}, scatter_kws={'color':'red', 'alpha': 0.3})
    if n%3 > 0:
        plt.ylabel('')

plt.show()

MSSubClass is the type of dwelling, and it is identified by numbers. This feature could be re ordered, but is probably best made into a categorical feature as that's what it really is.

KitchenAbvGr also has a strange behavior since the majority have 1, so it's highly influenced by the tail of the distribution. OverallCond suffers from a similar problem, and the regression line is the opposite of what we expect. These are good candidates for a transformation or removal.

GarageYrBlt seems to suffer from the 0s we filled in for null values. This feature is potentially be represented in GarageCars or GarageArea along with YearBuilt, and removed entirely or fill in the null values with something else. Two possibilities are the mean of the other values, or the YearBuilt. YearBuilt is what we will try first.

In [326]:
for n in range(0, len(data.GarageYrBlt)):
    if data.GarageYrBlt[n] == 0:
        data.loc[n, 'GarageYrBlt'] = data.YearBuilt[n]

After setting the zero values in GarageYrBlt to the values of YearBuilt, the graph for GarageYrBlt appears to be a more well behaved feature. It is very similar to YearBuilt and may or may not improve the model by dropping GarageYrBlt.

We will be using OneHotEncoding for the categorical data which is going to create a massive amount of new variables, and may overtrain out model. Another potential approach is encoding the categories in each feature as their respect mean with respect to the SalePrice.

Training the model¶

Full Log Prices¶

In [334]:
# Full Model of Log Prices
X = one_hot_encoded
y = np.log(data['SalePrice'])

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

my_model = XGBRegressor(n_estimators=1000, learning_rate=0.01)
my_model.fit(X_train, y_train, verbose=False)
predictions = my_model.predict(X_test)


# Graph of Actual vs Predicted Prices of Validation Set
plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))

plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
plt.scatter(x=y_test, y=predictions, c='navy', alpha=0.6)
plt.plot(y_train, y_train, color='cyan')

plt.xlim(10.9, 13.6)
plt.ylim(10.9, 13.6)

plt.xlabel('Actual log prices', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Prediced log prices', fontsize=14)
plt.title('Actual vs Predicted log prices', fontsize=17)

# Graph of Residuals of Validation Set

resid = predictions - y_test
plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
plt.scatter(x=predictions, y=resid, c='#e74c3c', alpha=0.6)

plt.xlabel('Predicted prices', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Residuals', fontsize=14)
plt.title('Residuals vs Fitted Values', fontsize=17)

# Graph of Residual Distribution of Validation Set

plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)

plt.title('Residual Distribution', fontsize=17)
sns.distplot(resid)

plt.show()

Full Model of Log Prices with transformed features¶

In [338]:
# Full Model of Log Prices with transformed features

# Feature transformations
transformed_data = one_hot_encoded.copy()

def log(feature):
    transformed_data[feature] = np.log1p(transformed_data[feature].values)

def quadratic(feature):
    transformed_data[feature+'_squared'] = transformed_data[feature]**2


log('GrLivArea')
log('1stFlrSF')
log('2ndFlrSF')
log('TotalBsmtSF')
log('LotArea')
log('LotFrontage')
log('KitchenAbvGr')
log('GarageArea')

quadratic('OverallQual')
quadratic('YearBuilt')
quadratic('YearRemodAdd')
quadratic('TotalBsmtSF')
quadratic('2ndFlrSF')
quadratic('GrLivArea')

transformed_data['HasBasement'] = transformed_data['TotalBsmtSF'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x > 0 else 0)
transformed_data['HasGarage'] = transformed_data['GarageArea'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x > 0 else 0)
transformed_data['Has2ndFloor'] = transformed_data['2ndFlrSF'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x > 0 else 0)
transformed_data['HasMasVnr'] = transformed_data['MasVnrArea'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x > 0 else 0)
transformed_data['HasWoodDeck'] = transformed_data['WoodDeckSF'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x > 0 else 0)
transformed_data['HasPorch'] = transformed_data['OpenPorchSF'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x > 0 else 0)
transformed_data['HasPool'] = transformed_data['PoolArea'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x > 0 else 0)

X = transformed_data
y = np.log(data['SalePrice'])

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

my_model = XGBRegressor(n_estimators=1000, learning_rate=0.01)
my_model.fit(X_train, y_train, verbose=False)
predictions = my_model.predict(X_test)


# Graph of Actual vs Predicted Prices of Validation Set
plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))

plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
plt.scatter(x=y_test, y=predictions, c='navy', alpha=0.6)
plt.plot(y_train, y_train, color='cyan')

plt.xlim(10.9, 13.6)
plt.ylim(10.9, 13.6)

plt.xlabel('Actual log prices', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Prediced log prices', fontsize=14)
plt.title('Actual vs Predicted log prices', fontsize=17)

# Graph of Residuals of Validation Set

resid = predictions - y_test
plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
plt.scatter(x=predictions, y=resid, c='#e74c3c', alpha=0.6)

plt.xlabel('Predicted prices', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Residuals', fontsize=14)
plt.title('Residuals vs Fitted Values', fontsize=17)

# Graph of Residual Distribution of Validation Set

plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)

plt.title('Residual Distribution', fontsize=17)
sns.distplot(resid)
